WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.920
It has been 14 years since the phrase data is the new oil was first used.

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:18.040
This phrase was coined by Cliff Harville, implying that just as oil needs to be refined

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:24.840
into gas, chemicals, plastics, etc., data must be broken down and analysed for it to

00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:25.840
have value.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:28.240
But what if it is not?

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:33.680
Of what value is the data if it is open, accessible, but not usable?

00:00:33.680 --> 00:00:39.520
Hi, my name is Shalmith Kariuki and I'm here to talk about a small project I embarked on

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:41.680
in March 2020.

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:50.520
rKenyaCensus is a package that contains the 2019 Kenya Population and Housing Census results.

00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:55.880
The Population Census exercise was held in August and this was the first time that Kenya

00:00:55.880 --> 00:01:02.119
was using technology for both cartographic mapping and enumeration.

00:01:02.119 --> 00:01:07.919
The survey questionnaire covered areas such as population characteristics, agriculture,

00:01:07.919 --> 00:01:15.480
education, information communication and technology, henceforth referred to as ICT, etc.

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:21.639
This data was published in four PDF files, which can be found on the Kenya National Bureau

00:01:21.639 --> 00:01:24.400
of Statistics website.

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:26.239
Now, is this data open?

00:01:26.239 --> 00:01:29.199
Yes, it is available on the website.

00:01:29.199 --> 00:01:30.199
Is it accessible?

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:37.080
Yes, anyone can download it, but is it usable in its current format?

00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:38.959
But why do we even care?

00:01:38.959 --> 00:01:43.599
Why is usability important?

00:01:43.599 --> 00:01:47.000
Let us look at one of the aspects covered in the survey, ICT.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.599
We are going to look at the influence that ICT has had on education in Kenya during the

00:01:52.599 --> 00:01:53.599
COVID pandemic.

00:01:53.599 --> 00:01:56.839
But first, a few statistics.

00:01:56.839 --> 00:02:02.120
According to a new report by UNICEF, two out of three school-age children do not have internet

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:03.599
access at home.

00:02:03.599 --> 00:02:09.720
In fact, the number of unconnected pupils is higher in Africa and Asia as compared to

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:11.839
the rest of the world.

00:02:11.839 --> 00:02:18.520
The first COVID case was announced in Kenya on 12 March and two days after, the government

00:02:18.520 --> 00:02:23.039
announced closure of schools and institutions were encouraged to move their learning online.

00:02:23.039 --> 00:02:27.600
The Ministry of Education also made a directive for the curriculum teaching to be delivered

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:31.839
via radio, TV, YouTube and other digital platforms.

00:02:31.839 --> 00:02:34.600
And so, online learning began.

00:02:34.600 --> 00:02:36.720
Kenyans adapted very quickly.

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:40.479
One university trained their students and staff and also entered into a partnership

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:45.639
with a mobile network operator to ensure that their staff received cheaper data bundles

00:02:45.639 --> 00:02:48.800
specifically for e-learning.

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:54.479
Several other institutions did their best to heed to the government's directive.

00:02:54.479 --> 00:02:59.240
Entertainment programs were aired on TV during school hours and young kids quickly learned

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:04.000
how to use tools such as Zoom and Google Hangouts.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:07.279
But then, online learning was not going well for everyone.

00:03:07.279 --> 00:03:12.720
Leaders from semi-arid areas came out claiming that online learning in their areas was just

00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:17.119
but a fallacy because their areas lacked basic infrastructure.

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:22.160
So, what basic infrastructure is required for smooth online learning?

00:03:22.160 --> 00:03:28.720
First, one will need a laptop or a mobile phone to access materials in electronic format.

00:03:28.720 --> 00:03:33.320
And these devices have to actually be connected to the internet so that you can actually access

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:37.399
this information and electricity is needed to power both.

00:03:38.119 --> 00:03:42.679
A lot of students took to social media to complain that online learning was not working

00:03:42.679 --> 00:03:43.679
for them.

00:03:43.679 --> 00:03:47.960
A lot claimed that they lacked the minimum basic requirements needed to partake in online

00:03:47.960 --> 00:03:48.960
learning.

00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:52.399
Electricity has also been a problem in Kenya.

00:03:52.399 --> 00:03:56.960
Even for us who have access to electricity, it's not reliable.

00:03:56.960 --> 00:04:00.839
I'm actually hoping that I'll be done with this presentation by the time lights go off.

00:04:00.839 --> 00:04:08.839
You can visit the Kenya Power Twitter handle to just see more of the complaints that we

00:04:08.839 --> 00:04:15.720
channel through that platform complaining about blackouts day in, day out.

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:20.279
Many families do not have the devices and internet access that enable children to take

00:04:20.279 --> 00:04:22.359
part in remote schooling.

00:04:22.359 --> 00:04:25.200
Let's take an example of two extreme cases.

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:27.119
Manzi comes from an average family.

00:04:27.119 --> 00:04:29.480
She has a bedroom of her own in their house.

00:04:29.679 --> 00:04:33.600
Manzi's father pays for internet at the end of each month and he recently purchased a

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:35.239
new laptop for her.

00:04:35.239 --> 00:04:40.920
Manzi attends Shule Kubwa, which is a university based in the capital city of Kenya, Nairobi.

00:04:40.920 --> 00:04:44.920
Charlie, on the other hand, comes from a humble background.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:49.440
His parents are not able to pay school fees for him and so he has to depend on the area's

00:04:49.440 --> 00:04:50.440
bursary fund.

00:04:50.440 --> 00:04:56.320
And after emerging top in the Kenya Secondary National Examination, Charlie got a scholarship

00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:59.440
to also attend Shule Kubwa.

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:04.359
So Charlie and Manzi, together with some of the friends they grew up with, are in the

00:05:04.359 --> 00:05:05.359
same class.

00:05:05.359 --> 00:05:09.760
And while in school, they are subjected to the same conditions, the same lecture room,

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:13.799
the same lecture period, the same exam, and so on.

00:05:13.799 --> 00:05:15.920
But what happens now that they're at home?

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:18.000
Well, Manzi is actually very happy.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:22.600
She gets to seclude herself in her room during class sessions.

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:27.320
And while on her break, she's able to enjoy her favorite comedy on Netflix.

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:29.399
But then for Charlie, he's actually depressed.

00:05:29.399 --> 00:05:37.839
He's even thinking of repeating the current class because he feels he has been left behind.

00:05:37.839 --> 00:05:42.640
After six months, schools reopened for a small subset of students, those preparing for the

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:44.720
national examinations.

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:49.880
In Kenya, national examinations take place at the end of each year.

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:56.399
Now, an effective education response to the COVID-19 pandemic needs to be built on evidence

00:05:56.480 --> 00:05:57.480
and data.

00:05:57.480 --> 00:06:00.000
For example, what do we know about our population?

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.440
How many families own radios and televisions?

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:08.040
And do children actually use and actually learn from these online platforms?

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:13.279
And that's why the development of our Kenya Census was important.

00:06:13.279 --> 00:06:15.440
Development of this package involved three steps.

00:06:15.440 --> 00:06:20.920
The first one was downloading the data from the Kenya National Bureau of Statistics website.

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:27.000
The second one involved cleaning, scrapping, cleaning, and manipulating the data.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:32.239
I used the TabuLaser package to scrap the data and Tidyverse and some bizarre functions

00:06:32.239 --> 00:06:34.399
for cleaning and manipulating it.

00:06:34.399 --> 00:06:37.160
The third step was the actual package development.

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:42.160
And I'm very grateful to the authors of DevTools, TestFat, and UseThis who have made package

00:06:42.160 --> 00:06:43.760
development very easy.

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:48.839
I'm also grateful to Hadley and Jenny for the R packages book that is written in such

00:06:48.839 --> 00:06:57.040
a simple language, such that it is easy to understand some of the concepts covered.

00:06:57.040 --> 00:07:01.880
For consistency, the data sets were named in a similar manner as the tables in the published

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:02.880
documents.

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:09.160
So V1 and S42.1 is actually Table 2.1 in Volume 1.

00:07:09.160 --> 00:07:12.600
Data cleaning and manipulation skills are really important in this task.

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:18.399
I had to deal with a lot of trailing and leading spaces, extra white spaces, blank spaces,

00:07:18.399 --> 00:07:19.399
and other weird characters.

00:07:19.399 --> 00:07:25.000
I also needed to restructure the data by generating new variables that distinguished counties

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:26.000
from sub-counties.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:32.279
I'm grateful to the R4DS community, especially Scott and Stephen who are of great help when

00:07:32.279 --> 00:07:40.160
I encountered errors while coding, while I still battle with rejects up to date.

00:07:40.160 --> 00:07:44.799
I also created a small Shiny app where anyone, especially those who do not use R, could download

00:07:44.799 --> 00:07:50.320
the data in either .csv or .xlsx format.

00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:55.480
Now could some of this data have helped us to determine whether Kenya was ready for online

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:56.480
learning?

00:07:56.480 --> 00:07:58.720
Let's have a look.

00:07:58.720 --> 00:08:03.959
This map shows the proportion of households where the main type of lighting is electricity.

00:08:03.959 --> 00:08:07.760
The data can be found in Volume 4, Table 2.19.

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:11.839
So in essence, in the data, it's going to be V4 underscore 2.19.

00:08:11.839 --> 00:08:14.640
The darker the region, the higher the proportion.

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:19.320
The darkest region is the capital city of Kenya, which is Nairobi.

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:24.160
Most regions in the semi-arid areas, that's the light yellow regions, use either burnt

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:27.679
wood, torches, or paraffin lamps as a source of light.

00:08:27.679 --> 00:08:30.079
Charlie comes from one of these areas.

00:08:30.079 --> 00:08:35.840
In case anyone is curious, these maps were created using SF and ggplot2.

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:43.280
The pattern is the same when we look at access to computers or laptops and usage of the internet.

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:48.640
Areas that have high population based in the rural areas tend to be at a disadvantage.

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:53.200
There's no way Charlie could have reaped the benefits of online learning as much as Manzi

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:55.919
would have, even at a bare minimum.

00:08:55.919 --> 00:09:01.359
If this kind of analysis was available beforehand, the insights obtained could have helped the

00:09:01.359 --> 00:09:08.799
government and stakeholders make better decisions regarding learning during the COVID pandemic.

00:09:08.880 --> 00:09:13.440
The data has been used by the International Center for Humanitarian Affairs, which is

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:18.559
part of the Red Cross, to assess COVID-19 high-risk areas in Kenya.

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:24.159
It's my prayer that most entities will adopt this data to develop insights that will help

00:09:24.159 --> 00:09:26.880
drive development in Kenya.

00:09:26.880 --> 00:09:33.200
And to conclude, we have only touched on the ICT part of this data.

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:36.239
In essence, only two out of 74 tables.

00:09:36.320 --> 00:09:41.599
Imagine how much information we could get if we analysed all the census data, and imagine

00:09:41.599 --> 00:09:46.000
how much more information and insights we could get if we converted all the datasets

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:52.880
that are lying in various websites into machine-readable formats that are easy to analyse.

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:57.119
Insights obtained from this data will help the country prepare itself better for the

00:09:57.119 --> 00:09:59.119
next calamity.

00:09:59.119 --> 00:10:03.280
R is an open source language, and there are so many learning resources online.

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:07.760
It's up to us as R developers and R users to use the knowledge and skills we have to

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:14.239
develop tools that will help us in solving problems that exist in our society.

00:10:14.239 --> 00:10:15.919
Thank you for listening to me.

00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:16.960
Questions are welcome.

